@context: Checkout flow with a React Datepicker custom control. Demonstrates that complex UI widgets can be driven by a Python handler registered via @custom_control, while the .hunt file stays readable plain English.
@blueprint: demo_custom_controls

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PREREQUISITE: pages.json must map the checkout URL to "Checkout Page".
#
# Example pages.json entry:
#   {
#     "https://example-shop.com/": {
#       "Domain": "Example Shop",
#       "https://example-shop.com/checkout": "Checkout Page"
#     }
#   }
#
# The custom handler for "React Datepicker" lives in:
#   controls/demo_custom.py
#
# The engine loads that file at startup via load_custom_controls(CWD).
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. NAVIGATE to https://example-shop.com/checkout

# The engine resolves the current page name as "Checkout Page" via pages.json.
# When it sees 'React Datepicker' as the target, get_custom_control() returns
# our Python handler from controls/demo_custom.py.
# Standard DOM heuristics and AI resolution are bypassed entirely.

2. Fill 'React Datepicker' with '2026-12-25'

# The rest of the steps use normal heuristic/AI resolution — no custom controls
# needed for standard HTML form elements.

3. Fill 'Email' field with 'ghost@manul.ai'
4. Fill 'Full Name' field with 'Ghost Manul'
5. Select 'Express Shipping' from the 'Shipping Method' dropdown
6. Click the 'Place Order' button
7. VERIFY that 'Order confirmed' is present.
8. DONE.
